The name of Terentius Scaurus, the author of a Latin grammar and a controversial treatise against Caesellius Vindex, as well as of com- mentaries on Plautus and Virgil, brings us into the reign of Hadrian. Gellius calls him (xr xv 3) ‘ divi Hadriani temporibus grammaticus vel nobilissimus.’ His grammatical works are cited by Gellius and the later grammarians: of his commentary on Virgil so little is expressly quoted that it would be rash to pronounce any judgment upon its merits. In A. 111 484, ‘nec cedit honori,' Servius tells us that Scaurus read ‘ honore! 13. IULIUS HATERIANUS.

Haterianus is mentioned as a commentator on Virgil by Macrobius (111 viii 2), and several times in the Verona scholia. He is assumed by the historians of Latin literature to be the Haterianus who is quoted as an authority by Trebellius Pollio in his history of the thirty tyrants (Script. Hist. Aug.
